Ambassador to the EU Vice-President:
The Czechs have a reputation of ill-wishers and skeptics in relation to the euro.
“The Lisbon Treaty has caused significant differences between individual organisations.”
"I didn't expect there would be such a brutal war."
“It will take five or six years before the situation somehow stabilizes, calms down and all the players get used to their new roles,” EU Ambassador Milena Vicenova rigidly began her lecture at the Faculty of Law.
She proved how much she adheres to her motto “Clearly and openly about Europe” in the first part of her lecture, where she described individual EU institutions and the relations between them so simply and clearly that many lecturers from the KU Faculty of Law would envy.
Moreover, Vicenova praised the work of the new permanent President of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
“At first, critics said he was an ordinary grey office mouse who couldn’t play any role; I have to say, everyone was amazed at how well he handled his role.”
“He is a man who can listen to the 27 member states at the same time, who is great to communicate with and who has a clear idea of which direction the EU needs to develop.”
She explained her new position as a representative for international relations and security as an answer to the question: "Who is the European Union? By what number should I call?"; i.e. as an important step towards the unification and greater transparency of the Union's policy towards countries such as China or India.
No one is going to ban our cheese.
Vicenova further focused on a programme that is key for the EU in the past, present and near future.
She called the Czech presidency a success last year.
The Czechs were dealing with an impending financial crisis; they overcame that crisis and organized the Eastern Partnership summit.
She said that the resignation of the government at that time was a negative phenomenon that caused considerable damage to the Czech Republic.
Currently, Czech representatives in the EU are very busy.
As the Ambassador said, both the presidency and the subsequent financial crisis have caused an ongoing ferment.
In addition, it is necessary to adopt a new seven-year EU budget, which is very difficult, given the current crisis.
Whether the budget will be scarce and economical, which areas will be preferred; which countries will receive more support and which will receive less; all these issues are in the upcoming program.
The ambassador recalled the key slogans that she brought to Brussels: “On Europe, Intelligible Language”.
“I really don’t like abbreviations, foreign words and jargon that nobody understands.
How can citizens understand that in Brussels people are not trying to sell curves or round cucumbers, bananas of different sizes, or that someone is going to ban our varieties of cheese.
It is also going to make better use of the EU environment and attract more Czechs to European organizations.
Multi-speed Europe is our future
The ambassador claims that the Czechs are considered Euro-skeptics; as well as people who note the negative rather than the positive sides of things.
She wants more representatives of the Czech Republic to be involved in European organizations.
She believes that several factors are to blame: for example, the modesty of our candidates and their inability to write motivational letters; at the same time with a little support from the Czech side.
Along with the successful chairmanship of the Czech Republic, she noted the power and cooperation of the Visegrad Group.
“Believe me, when I meet someone from Poland and Hungary, and a Slovak joins us, the Frenchman next to me says, ‘Hey, what’s up with the Visegrad group again?’ and he’s not happy about it.”
In the future, the Vicenova Union expects mainly new strict rules for the budgetary policy of the member states.
Compared to the new European Federation, she sees the idea of a two-speed, if not multi-speed Europe as more realistic.
“We have both countries inside and outside the eurozone.”
“We have the Schengen area, and we already have the institute of enhanced cooperation.”
“For the first time, it has been said that countries that want to unite, while those that don’t, can stay away.”
“The number of such institutions will grow; it will be a truly two-speed Europe,” Vicenova expects.
In this regard, she stressed the role of both the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in promoting the rule that all EU-wide issues should be discussed by all member states, not just eurozone members.
History of the brand:
The innovator IBM is entering the second century of its existence.
If someone wants to find the word that best expresses IMB’s strategy, the closest is likely to be “long-lasting.”
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered very modern, although it was founded more than a hundred years ago.
The longevity of the company was laid down by its first boss, the dreamer Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He believed in his motto that many of the world’s problems could be easily solved if people wanted to think.
His slogan “Think!” thus became the stamp around which the life of the future giant unfolded (as well as the name of its internal magazine, which IMB began to publish in 1935).
Moreover, it was the foundation of the corporate culture that Watson carefully built.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking means constantly moving towards the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a hundred years because it remained true to its original values, although it was not afraid to change everything around it.
In our first hundred years, it has enabled us to transform technology, business and company.
For the second hundred years, we hope to achieve even more,” says the current head of the company Samuel J. Palmizano on the occasion of the anniversary.
Complicated system
