IBM's history: from cheese knife to spaceflight.
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago. Its original name "Corporation of calculation, tabulation, recording" was quite complex.
It took the name IBM in 1924. Initially, the brand was called so, used for the company's offices in Canada and South America.
The foundations of the future IBM were laid by the merger of four companies, the history of which begins in the 1880s.
They owned technologies such as the legendary “table clock”, i.e. a clock that records the time when employees come and go from work.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlet Flint, who until 1930 also headed the board of trustees of the company.
Flint hired the director of a rival company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
Then the head pushed the founder of IBM into the shadows - Watson's ideas remain the basis of an inviolable corporate culture and personality.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name implies, started with the production and sale of various equipment for business - from cheese knives and meat cutters to cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson’s leadership, revenue doubled to $9 million, and the company’s large-scale expansion to all continents began.
Watson became so important to the company that nearly forty years later his seat as director was taken by his son, Thomas Watson, Jr.
Under his leadership, IBM began to develop artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both IBM employees and computers helped NASA control the space flights to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969, the human flight to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM line System/360.
The classic PC that defined the computer standards of the time, called the IBM 5150, appeared on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold the computers to a Chinese company, Lenovo, while buying the consulting division of PricewaterhouseCoopers, thus fully concentrating on consulting and high-value-added services.
Over the past three years, IBM has made great strides with its Smarter Planet concept.
Its aim is to make smart use of technology in areas where it has not yet been planned and to improve the road situation and urban management.
In the field of commerce, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform, which helps businessmen control the entire trading cycle.
The IBM tradition is strong even in our country.
In the former Czechoslovakia, as the first country located simultaneously in Central and Eastern Europe, IBM founded its branch in 1932.
Today, IBM CZ also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters of Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague, where also operates a world-class research group engaged in speech recognition.
