The dynamics of prices for travel since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies could operate in the former Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Since travel to the West was severely restricted, travel agencies of the time mostly sold tours to socialist bloc countries.
Thus, Czech tourists went on vacation to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia. Then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which entailed significant restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel individually to socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to go by himself, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, an invitation letter from that country was required; otherwise an individual trip was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies offered travel to the West, but had to either stand in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or have “good friends” in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
Currency authorization was necessary for travel to the West. It was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without a currency permit, it was impossible to obtain cash (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
Most often, Czechs spent their holidays at home, which led to the emergence of a large number of cottages and summer houses, this habit persists to this day.
After 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic thus experienced a real revolution.
While prior to 1989, holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were the culmination of our travels, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox, which we are no longer aware of, is that until 1989 we could not freely visit the most popular Croatia today, since it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the very beginning of 1990, the need to obtain a visa to the neighboring countries of Western Europe was abolished. This marked the beginning of a huge wave of short trips mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of traveling to the West. Everyone wanted to go there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents, as their income at that time was not enough for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring their own food (canned food, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech koruna. Decades later, our tourists can finally freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income increased, which led to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has allowed travel agencies to prepare regular flights operated by charter airlines. Compared to the past, air travel has now become incredibly cheap thanks to the ability to order bulk discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all developed world countries except the United States. This made our travels even easier.
The next significant event in the history of post-revolution travel occurred in 2000. Great demand led to the historically first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have brought Czech tourists to warm exotic countries. This winter, flights from the Czech Republic will depart to twelve exotic destinations.
Currently, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, occurred in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished the need to obtain a visa for Czech tourists. Thus, our country has permanently joined the most developed countries of the world.
For the first time in history in 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history they spent more than 15 thousand crowns per person during their vacation abroad, including their expenses at their destination.
