21st Century House in Vienna
Pavilion in a new place
Ingeborg Winsowski
An architectural story with ups, downs and a happy ending. Austria’s pavilion for the 1958 World’s Fair in Brussels won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, was empty and was abandoned.
It is now being re-opened as an exhibition centre.
The Austrian Pavilion, designed by Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 World's Fair in Brussels, is a famous example of modern post-war architecture with its simple forms, glass halls, bold ones that expressed faith in technological progress.
The Schwantzer Pavilion won the Grand Prix of Architecture in 1958 for its light, soaring steel and glass construction.
The building is considered a landmark in modern architecture.
This made the architect so famous that he also built the pavilion of Austria at the next World Exhibition.
In the end, he became famous worldwide in 1973 with his legendary four-cylinder BMW tower and her sister - a building in the shape of a bowl.
The pavilion, conceived as a temporary exhibition building, was moved to the Swiss Garden near Vienna's South Station, transformed and opened as a 20th-century museum in 1962 - and is often referred to as the "House of the 20th Century" for this reason.
However, the building was not suitable for the museum for technical and spatial reasons - it did not have walls on which works of art could be hung, and poor air conditioning.
However, it continued to be used until modern art in Vienna was given a new home.
The house has been empty since 2001 and its condition has been getting worse and worse.
Architect Adolf Kriszanitz has restored the pavilion, which has been called the “House of the 21st Century” and will be used as a museum of modern art.
This museum is a branch of the Belvedere Museum, which will open the first exhibition on Tuesday evening - in every sense a joyful event.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery in 2007, contributed to the new venture.
Husslein-Arco, a graduate of the Faculty of Art History with a brilliant career as a figure skater in her youth, who worked at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and eventually became the founder and director of the Museum of Modernity in Salzburg, convinced politicians and curators to continue the reconstruction, attracted public funds and private donations, and made a decision to donate.
The new museum was to accommodate the permanent exhibition of the Fritz Votruba Foundation, a cafe and a bookstore along with modern art. An office building was also to be built.
Strict control & limited budget
Krishanitz was then the ideal candidate for the project.
He was known, of course, for the restoration and expansion of Josef Olbrich's Vienna Secession, and won the competition, but he also studied with Schwantzer at the Vienna University of Technology, and the pavilion was an "extremely important place" for him, where he attended exhibitions "almost every week".
He knew the original design and knew the challenges facing the building, a building that had already lost some of its grandeur and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and transformed.
The problems that arose during the last perestroika were much more serious. The building was an “energy absorber,” says Krishanitz.
The window profiles on the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade were replaced, a fiberglass-reinforced safety glass was inserted, and the glass roof was replaced with high-strength safety glass.
The steel beams of the thermal bridge were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos was removed from the ceilings.
The two lower floors have created space for new use of the building, the fallen light well between the building and the street provides lighting – a virtually new building, but still an elegant Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors were preserved, and the building was painted in the old red-brown color of corrosion protection.
The cinema hall is the same as it used to be.
All this with strict control of the museum management and with a limited budget.
“We often had to find material that was good, cheap and would have been approved by the museum management,” says Krishanitz, pointing to the uneven flooring in the basement.
The building remained flexible and light, despite limitations, challenges and transformations.
Krishanitz recently noticed that the Brussels Pavilion was rough – a typical “drops in the city” story.
Such an architecture is "always out of place" and nevertheless wants to "stimulate real awareness."
The 21st century house is in a very right place, because when planning the city there was an unexpected luck. A completely redesigned "main station quarter" with offices and residential real estate is growing around the Swiss Garden.
A second happy event may occur. The 21st century house can be supplemented by a second Krishanitz building – collector Francesca von Habsburg has acquired the Berlin Temporary Exhibition Hall and is reportedly in talks with the city about its location next door in the Swiss Garden.
