"And if there is something, it means that they have long adapted to Anglo-Saxon customs."
Indeed, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, brought it its first big profits - and then a fiasco. No other financial institution in Europe has lost as much money in the jungle of subprime assets as the largest Swiss bank.
The disaster became apparent on October 15, 2008.
“On Wednesday, the ruling coalition of a small country of seven million people undertook the largest rescue operation in the history of the country,” writes Lucas Hessig in his book Crash UBS.
Politicians approved the allocation of 68 billion Swiss francs (about 45 billion euros) to save the bank from bankruptcy.
How could this have happened?
If you ask Swiss banks, they will say that the problem is mainly the size of UBS.
Two of the three largest Swiss banks merged into one large group in June 1998.
A bank was formed that was already too big for little Switzerland at the time of the merger – and a bank that continued to grow.
This was helped by the fact that the two banks that formed UBS complemented each other. One was a rich but powerful bank specializing in asset management in Zurich; the other was not so rich, but much more internationalized.
Internationalized investment bankers suddenly gained access to a large amount of money that they could use to spin the all-powerful wheel.
Two names are associated with the growth of UBS: Peter Wolffley, CEO of the UBS Group from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, Chairman of the Board of Directors.
“I’ve always believed that Wolffley and Ospel are a dream team,” said Hans Geiger, a banking analyst.
“Wolffley, an outstanding intellectual, modest and deeply understanding of models and statistics, and Ospel, with his inner instinct, went all the way up, starting with an intern at a bank.”
But Ospel eventually relied on Woolfley.
And Wolffley could have made a critical mistake. "He thought his models were real," Geiger says.
"It's tragic."
Maybe it's tragic.
Pride precedes defeat.
UBS employees remember meetings of board members, at which Woolfley always repeated the same slogan - to move Goldman Sachs.
The Bank of America was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
At that time, he headed the "tournament table", where the successes of banks were made.
UBS wanted to get to the very top of this table.
He was able to make part of that journey.
UBS was the largest player in currency and government securities trading.
Authorized management consultants, however, pointed to a weakness. According to the parameter, which in banking terminology is called "constant income", UBS was far behind the largest banks.
UBS has had failures in U.S. mortgage products.
To plug the hole, UBS got involved in an adventure that nearly cost him his life.
In an effort to grow, the bank and its hedge fund invested in U.S. subprime securities.
This evolved into a large mechanism that pooled securities based on U.S. mortgages and sold them further – while continuing to bear the risks itself.
Even when other banks have long been looking for a way out of this process, UBS has not stopped.
“UBS bought until the summer of 2007, when the U.S. real estate market was already on fire,” says banking analyst Geiger.
The higher the rise, the deeper the fall.
One manager after another had to leave as attempts to get the bank in order proved more difficult than it seemed at first.
Posts at UBS have turned into a children's game with chairs and to this day remain unreliable.
To anyone who will lead this huge bank, there is an almost impossible task.
He must find a strategy for a bank that has turned its back on all existing business models.
Banking analyst Geiger already has an idea - to abandon investment banking, focus on asset management and forget about their Swiss roots.
The bank, however, is not (yet) ready to go that far.
Nevertheless, it is obvious that investment activities need to be significantly narrowed.
The new head of the bank, Sergio Hermotti, plans to present his future strategy on Tuesday.
