Smart Crows Fill Cities
Graci are considered problem birds in many places. Experts today say that these very smart birds will no longer be able to drive out of cities.
Some love birds, others would like to get rid of them as quickly as possible. Crows have been part of the urban landscape for centuries, but residents complaining of dirt and noise are becoming more and more in many settlements.
The problem of birds, however, is far from being solved.
At the first symposium on crows, in the city of Ler in East Frisia, experts argued that it was no longer possible to expel gracs from cities.
Experts from all over Germany discussed possible solutions.
Searching for alternatives in cities
Conservationists argued that the root of the problem in cities was the migration of specially protected gracs, pointing out that the use of chemicals in agriculture was increasingly destroying traditional habitats.
Hunting, expanding construction and cutting down of traditional nesting trees made life difficult for birds.
The crows are under guard.
In the city of Zest in Westphalia and in the north-west in Jever, Dipholz, Achim near Bremen and Lera there are large colonies, numbering more than 600 parent pairs.
A controversial project to shoot ravens in Lera caused disapproving newspaper headlines in 2005.
Critics have described trapping birds and cramming them with sticks as particularly cruel.
“Normal movement and scaring do not give anything,” said architect and landscape designer Werner Clever of Lehr.
Knocking down nests with a jet of water or felling trees often have undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser of Lara, Baden-W<0xC3><0xBC>rttemberg.
“Animals disperse and large colonies divide and spread to other areas.”
Scaring is possible only in the form of an exception near hospitals, nursing homes and schools.
"We have to live with them. Getting rid of them is not an option."
In isolation from the surrounding areas, the problem in the cities will not be solved, says Mayor Lera Wolfgang K<0xC3><0xB6>lner.
A combination of deterring birds from needing protection in residential areas and encouraging them to return to other areas could be a way out.
"Information stands instead of chainsaws" was the slogan proposed by psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jurgens, who advocates a completely different approach to birds. "We need to be confident in order to live with this problem."
J<0xC3><0xBC>rgens was one of the founders of the educational crow route in Ascherberg in Schleswig-Holstein, where information stands provide information about the lives of very clever ogres.
