Peter Englund’s intense and very good new book, Beauty and Sorrow: A Personal History of the First World War, begins with a long list of characters that makes your heart stop.
Here’s a tip on how to read on: Carefully cut out this page and use it as a bookmark.
You will get to know these people very closely as Mr. Englund narrates, and this list of characters will be your GPS, your beacon in those moments when, like one of these men and women, you will stray off the road and get lost in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he’s written now is unusual, he describes it, quite accurately, as “working on anti-history.”
It has few known names, important treaties, or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors, deft journalists, or discussions of tactics and military equipment.
It's not so much a book about what was, he explains, as "a book about what it looked like." It's about "feelings, impressions, experiences and state of mind."
The book “Beauty and Sorrow” weaves together the experience of 20 years of war more or less unremarkable men and women, on both sides of the front line, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and employees.
Some of these people are going to be heroes.
Someone will get captured, lose an arm or a leg, go crazy or die.
Their lives twinkle here like church candles: new ones are added to many others, and some are extinguished at this time.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of history books.
