Walls have eyes: How researchers study you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just an ordinary guy exposing his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to a mass murder in Norway in July that killed 77 people, appeared at his first public court hearing.
Although Breivik could act alone, he was far from alone on the network: he spent much time preparing to attack his computer, communicating with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how do we find them?
It's easy - you just need to go to Facebook.
“We realized that getting to them is not difficult at all,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European cyber-populism by the British research center DEMOS.
The stock of personal data on Facebook is so large, Bartlett says, that researchers could easily use the site’s advertising tool to highlight the necessary demographic with scientific precision — something marketers have been doing for several years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million right-wing group fans across Europe and then pitched them an ad, but instead of showing a new group or diet product, the ad offered the user a survey that asked questions about their level of education, attitudes toward violence, and optimism about their own future.
Using Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 members of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries — even without leaving the office.
“It’s a whole new way of doing research,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are often young men who are dissatisfied with immigration.
“Those who combine their online activity with offline activity are more intelligent, more democratic, and less aggressive than those who just hide behind a monitor.”
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to explore everything from health issues to social trends, which are expressed in ‘Likes’, wall posts, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three posts a day, Facebook’s “super-relevant information” is causing a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the site’s title in the title by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it provides an opportunity to study people who can not be approached on the street with a notebook.
“Earlier, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them.”
“You’d have to join the party, and they’d never accept you,” Bartlett says.
“Facebook excludes all of this – you address them directly.”
Others say that with the help of this site it would be possible to identify and investigate social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their drunken exploits on Facebook were significantly more at risk of alcoholism than students who kept quiet about it.
Moreno suggests that students’ peers, such as their dorm mentors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who updates drunken statuses too often.
“You can’t solve a problem without identifying it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior, and Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute.
“We found a way to identify children at risk who would not otherwise be detected.”
Facebook is also constantly retrieving various kinds of data about its users.
The site’s data processing team processed statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, mid-term voter turnout in 2010, and the National Happiness Index (mostly using information only they have access to—cyberfreedom champions have long insisted that the site should make its extensive data collection publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what about when Facebook users become participants in a study they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strictly defined standards for conducting offline research, online data is publicly available.
“I don’t think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher can observe their profiles,” says Neil Selvin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a study he conducted in 2006 using public student pages on Facebook.
“As far as they could imagine, it was just between them and their friends.”
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline there is no guarantee that the object of study is extremely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much information in the profile and on the user's page is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selvin says.
That’s why, despite years of work in technology research, Selvin thinks that the notebook and pen are still the best research tools you can use.
“Nothing can replace going out into the real world and communicating with real people,” he says.
“Social research is supposed to be about social, and much of social is still happening offline.”
