7 Lessons From Steve Jobs' Lost Interview Show at the Theater This Week
After Steve Jobs's death on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing the technical genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans might consider the biggest discovery in a newly-discovered interview, which was recalled ahead of previews in major markets this week, is how much that creative mind understood in business processes and manufacturing technology.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer, and considered himself a hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and modernizer of the production process, who believed that many business executives suffered from "the pain of thinking that a really great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] a great idea from a great product separates a huge amount of skilled labor."
Back in 1995, Bob Kringley created the television series Nerds Triumph about the advent of the personal computer, and he spent more than an hour with Jobs for a unique long conversation.
By that time, it was about 10 years since Jobs was kicked out of Apple, and he was already working full-time at his new computer company, NeXT, in anticipation of mass Internet adoption.
While a small portion of Kringley’s interview was used in the Nerds, he says the originals of the interview went missing during transportation.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was found in the director's garage.
This footage, slightly edited, became the basis for the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which comes out at Landmark Theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hatred of detailed interviews, Jobs seems unusually willing to lay out his technology philosophy and business strategy here.
And incredibly thoughtful.
At four different points during the interview, there are large intervals between questions and answers – reflections of 10-15 seconds, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to be more precise.
There are also moments where Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems irritated by Kringley’s questions, forcing him to move faster to questions or phenomena of greater importance.
In the pre-Pixar era, iPods and iPhones, the Lost Interview has something ominously prophetic, as Jobs evaluates what he sees different companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision for the future of information technology.
It's one thing to read about Jobs' posthumous work evaluations, but there's something vulnerable and inspiring about Jobs that we see here, a troubled dreamer on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of what things could and should be.
Soon after he said everything here, he went and did it.
A brief summary of the seven significant findings of the Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"All the time in business, I kept asking, 'Why are you doing this?' And the answers you keep getting are, 'Oh, that's just how it's done.'
No one knows why they do what they do, no one thinks very deeply in business.
That's what I found out.
Jobs continues to detail his efforts to streamline reporting at Apple.
A frustrated way of recording expenses, often beginning with “standard expenses” that were taken from the ceiling and then adjusted with “clarification,” he created an automated structure that ensured that they could track business expenses down to the smallest detail.
Jokes about the Pope:
Jobs details the “blue box” he made with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed people to effectively hack into a phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device before, but Jobs’ euphoria here at describing the blue box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He recounts how he and Wozniak tested the box using a pay phone, ordering a conversation and then connecting from one AT&T network to another until they connected as many stations as possible.
“We’ve covered the globe half a dozen times, and you’re screaming at the payphone, and it’s a minute later, it’s coming into the next payphone,” Jobs says with a smile.
“We were young and all we learned was that we could make something that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us knew a little bit, but we could have mastered the little thing that could control the big thing — it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think without it Apple could ever have come along.
Jobs goes on to detail one famous prank that he and Wozniak practically handled by calling the Vatican through a blue box at midnight and asking for the Pope’s phone, struggling to copy Henry Kissinger.
When various members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to talk to an American diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the Pope himself was picked up to answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and the cold calling of Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to assemble the frequency meter, he found Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“It had a strong impact on me, it was the only company I saw at that age, and it shaped my view of what a company is and how well they treat their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the very first desktop computer.”
It was the size of a suitcase, it had a little monitor with an electron beam tube, and I fell in love with it.
I used to go to HP as a teenager and spin around that car and write programs for it.
About Improvised Innovation:
In several interviews, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the fly.
At the dawn of his career, when he went to sell a handful of circuit boards, one buyer asked him to assemble a whole computer.
Working only 30 days on credit, he had to think about both the assembly and delivery of finished devices.
Later at Apple, he recalls the difficulties he encountered developing a computer mouse:
“I remember furious arguments ... they were screaming at me that it would take five years [to assemble a mouse that would cost $300], and I was fed up and went out and found a designer.”
Ninety days later we had a mouse that we were able to collect for $15, which was incredibly reliable.
Some of the companies that are losing energy:
Long before he spearheaded Apple’s resurgence, Jobs foresaw exactly how many industry leaders would err in their vision of the situation and lose control of their market share.
“Suppose you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make the best copier or printer, and what?”
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company does not become more successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [these are the types of people] who end up coming to the leadership of the companies, and the people making the product are being pushed off the decision-making platform.
The product genius that led to this monopolistic position is being supplanted by people who have no idea of the difference between good and bad products – the required skill.
This is what happened to Xerox.
Xerox could take over the entire information technology industry.
It could be ten times bigger, it could be Microsoft of the 90s.
They were defeated by victory.
Innovation as an art form:
“A great idea is separated from a great product by a great deal of skillful work...when you spin a great idea, it changes and grows.”
You will learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are trade-offs you need to make – some things you can’t force to do are electrons, glass, robots, or factories.
You need to keep 5,000 ideas in your head — these concepts — connecting them all together.
Ultimately, it comes down to taste – it comes down to trying to express yourself in the best that people have ever produced, and later – trying to bring that into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have always been ashamed to steal great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh famous was that the people who worked on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happened to become the best information technology specialists in the world.
If it wasn’t for information technology, they’d be doing amazing things in other areas.
