How to catch a lie
A quick look at the latest headlines shows just how serious and pervasive deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain has been busy challenging allegations of sexual harassment from several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
The administration of the University of Pennsylvania was charged with perjury, as they allegedly hid that retired football coach raped boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught with a microphone on when he told US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lying destroys careers and shakes countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner has made a fool of himself by denying his anecdotes, which was quickly refuted by incontrovertible evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards was charged with financial fraud during a campaign to cover up extramarital affairs.
And again, no one living at the time will ever forget the media circus with President Bill Clinton, caught lying about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in office.
Stories of cheating on exams at school and college are common.
There were cases when teachers gave students answers to tests in order to have a good assessment of the results of their activities.
Mentors, who are supposed to teach the opposite, send a message that lies and fraud are acceptable.
How many lies do we face?
Over the course of one day, studies show that you can lie 10 to 200 times.
Now it is assumed that a significant part of this is a lie to salvation.
Another study found that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of dating each other.
Identifying a lie or incriminating a lie is a skill that everyone needs for both personal and professional purposes.
Unlike room games, like, say, charades, where you need to exclaim "I'm caught!", the detection of lies is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities engaged in comprehensive research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One result of the study is that most of the old myths about lies have been debunked.
The liars look me in the eye.
They do not always stagnate, stammer, blush or fuss.
It is not necessary to conclude from this that liars are difficult to notice and difficult to expose.
An experienced liar can get to the truth by observing the structure of the statements, facial expressions, the structure of the questions, and the temporal characteristics.
I have spent several years researching scientific discoveries in the vast and ever-growing segment of knowledge about lies, and it is clear that identifying lies is a modern skill that is easy to learn and that helps in navigating our complex world — especially if your professional responsibilities include recruiting, interviewing, negotiating, or managing.
Good liars are excellent at reading others, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men lie more about themselves, while women lie more about others, usually to protect someone’s feelings that married people lie less to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are most often brazen).
We also know that if you are perceived as a cheater, others will feel less guilty about cheating you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your object.
This is called "defining the initial state".
This helps provide a starting point for assessing changes further.
Observe the posture, laughter, voice characteristics of your object.
It would be good for you to know if a person is constantly knocking with his legs in a normal state, then you will not bring unfair accusations when you see a foot tap in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for groups of deceptive verbal and nonverbal actions.
Treat these groups as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceivers can fix the top of their body when they try to remember their story, they can put their feet towards the door, lean toward the exit, change their posture in a certain way, or show “relief after the interview” — that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture when all the difficult questions are behind.
Investigators often falsify the end-of-interview signal just to look at this relief after the interview.
So, pay attention to the speech of your object.
It is known that Scott Peterson stumbled and used the past time, claiming that his murdered wife is alive, which led to her search throughout the country.
Spiking people may also use distance in saying, “I didn’t have sexual relations with this woman...Miss Lewinsky,” or repeat the difficult question completely.
The most typical verbal indicators are barely perceptible.
Someone may use “qualifying language” when answering a difficult question: “Well... truth be told... as far as I know... as far as I know.”
This makes the answer more emotional than factual, and is often a red flag.
There is no magic way to detect a lie, but you can master the skill of detecting deception.
These skills will increase the chances of everyone not to become a victim of skillful crooks in professional and personal life.
