Climate change has slowed the economy
During the first year of Mario L<0xC3><0xB3>pez's rule, unemployment and the illegal labor market grew in Sinaloa, foreign funding declined and the economy was weakened.
2011 is the year that will go down in Sinaloa's economic history as related to the first year of the government of Mario L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Valdez, also called the year of change, which gave rise to great hopes for economic development, but given the adverse climatic conditions of the beginning of the year, there was no growth, but there was a decrease in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February not only led to millions of losses for the agricultural sector, but they limited the growth opportunities of the state economy, causing a reduction in economic activity by a total of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly due to a historic drop of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamics of other sectors of the economy.
According to the report on frost-affected areas provided by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 835.582 hectares were affected, of which 78.03 per cent were wholly affected and the remaining 21.07 per cent were partially affected.
The decline in economic activity caused, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, during the first three quarters was recorded an accelerated increase in the unemployment rate, from January to March 55,053 Sinaloa residents were unemployed, with a share of 4.53 percent of the economically active population, in the second quarter the share increased to 5.28 percent.
Decreased liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is due to many factors, for economist Gerardo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the Autonomous University (UAS), the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly by the actions that were taken in public policy.
“What we are seeing now is an increase in unemployment that is linked to several factors, including a loss of liquidity in the market to limit resources imposed by a law that was passed in Congress to fight money laundering, as people who illegally own dollars are not easy to work with, invest in and use for something,” he said.
Stopped Immigration
L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Cervantes said there was also a demographic factor in the rise in unemployment.
“The number of people who leave the state in search of work abroad in the United States has been limited, primarily because of the difficulties of entry, and in the second – because once they enter, they already face a lot of difficulties in finding work, so that a group of people remains and requires jobs here in the state, as a result, the unemployment rate increases,” he said.
Violation of formal requirements
Sinaloa’s labor market analysis gets worse if you look at the large number of violations that prevail in the working environment, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the state’s active population works without being mentioned as workers in any social protection institution.
In addition to unemployment and irregular clearance, another reminder of work in the state is represented by low wages; the state has the lowest salaries in the country, according to records from the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Ministry of Labor and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was 5,352 pesos until September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesos.
Reduction of FDI
In addition to a decline in economic activity and a high unemployment rate in 2011, the largest outflow of foreign direct investment in the last 10 years was recorded, according to the Ministry of Finance, from January to July, the state's FDI amounted to $630.697, which shows a drop of 87.74 percent compared to $5,143,312 during the same period last year.
For its part, the Department of Economic Development of the state government recorded only 17,280,000 pesos of investment during the year, which mainly accounted for companies from the service sector.
Debt
Amid the economic downturn, the state government asked in July during the state congress for approval of a loan of 3 billion pesos, which would be used to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 municipalities to revive the economy, only 2,600 million pesos were approved at the local level, and no debt benefits were expected in any sector of the state economy until November.
Reactions
For business representatives, the first year of the government of Mario L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Valdez demonstrates the lack of government capabilities.
Miguel Loredo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, president of the National Chamber of the Manufacturing Industry, said that during 2011 there was a lack of agreement on the wishes of various sectors, including the state government itself.
“The efficiency of the economy in Sinaloa this year was really low, we have to work hard to regain the positions lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble our efforts, we have not been able to coordinate the efforts of everyone and, above all, the good and synchronized work of the new government team, we hope that next year will be much better,” he said.
Deceleration of the economy
L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Loredo said events such as early frosts had halted the state’s economy this year and its efficiency and growth were limited.
“The low volumes of the economy are the result of several events, including frost, one of the main effects was a slow economy that is not fast enough to create an economic dynamic that allows us to have an acceptable level of processes, goods and services and, therefore, at the end of the year, we are closing it below our expectations,” he said.
Revising the direction
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said that the state needs to continue the most dynamic production activity.
“Overall, we found that we were working on it, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that will redefine the direction and economic course of the state, it is necessary to mobilize all the material and human resources that Sinaloa has,” he said.
Upcoming work
President Coparmex stressed the importance of determining the future direction in order to better guide the government’s efforts.
