The court will approve the “transition to digital television” in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analog signals with digital ones is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme Court has rejected constitutional claims made by the Senate and House of Representatives against a presidential decree that postpones the so-called “digital TV transition” from 2021 to 2015 because it failed to get the eight votes needed to annul it.
A minority of the four ministers, including the president of the court, Juan Silva Mesa, considered that President Felipe Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n had not exceeded his authority by issuing a decree detailing actions for the transition to digital terrestrial television.
