In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project in the sense that the federal executive power could not determine by general rules the measures for which the public administration should prepare.
“I also don’t believe that if this happened, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body,” and recalled that public policy planning in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, is relevant to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, the governance of the state.
Replacing analog signals with digital ones is one of the most important changes that has occurred in recent years, has led to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean postponing the benefits of the digital transformation, which involves meeting societal needs that have more than just a technical dimension, “as it covers economic, social, political and national security issues.”
These issues, he said, "require the work of the entire system, formed on the principle of state economic governance, includes a group of authorities, which the Constitution unites into the state executive power."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and did so with the help of the executive branch, despite the presence of highly specialized technical institutions.
