Italy’s appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet with Italy’s president on Wednesday to introduce a new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace said Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he could form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed largely of technocrats, though it is unclear when the new executive will take up its positions.
