When we have two or three songs that we haven’t played for a while, it keeps us in tune and surprises us because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved those songs and what we might have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and so I think it makes it more interesting for people.
This tour marks 20 years of your career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve done?
Yeah, absolutely.
First of all, I think none of us could ever have imagined that we would be in a rock band and that we’ve been doing that for over 20 years makes it like a dream.
We are very excited about our success and we are very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and we love making music.
We are happy to travel to places in the world where we have always wanted to go.
Everything is going very well for us.
What does it mean for you to be a significant part of the flowering of grunge?
It has always been an honor to be a part of this great group.
We are good friends with the guys from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It’s great when a movement grows out of a group of friends, and that’s unusual.
From time to time, one group from one city appears, but it is much more strange when five or ten groups appear at the same time in one city.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
I still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden during their tour, so we are happy to be friends with all of them and for us to be part of the Seattle sound that turned out.
It’s also very strange that a group like yours stays together and in the same band for so long.
Yes, the four of us were together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than many groups exist.
First, I think we're lucky we're still alive, and second, we care about others.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to this, musical paths have also been opened that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other’s music, and things couldn’t be better.
Your attitude to the word fame was not easy; but thanks to your success, you were able to do whatever you wanted.
How do you find balance?
As we grew up, it became easier to find balance.
We care about not being on tour for too long because it’s easy to get into this game of big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are here for the music, it reminds you that you have to respect the music and what made it, without deciding to be famous and be a rock star, something none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project, Manother Love Bone?
I think we write really good songs and at the beginning it was great.
We were a band for almost three years and never released an album until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
There were a lot of disappointments because it lasted so long, and most importantly, we are still close friends with Bruce (Fervezer) and Greg (Gilmore) who started with us in the band, and when I hear a song or see a photo, I think of the incredible person that Andy was, and as he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work.
He was a wonderful man and we miss him.
The local group Las Robertas will be responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you're familiar with her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her to open?
Yes, the producers sent us a few video offers and it was the band we liked the most so we can’t wait to see what Las Robertas has to offer live and it should be very exciting.
Why do you constantly change the words in Yellow Ledbetter at concerts?
It's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he's using the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
There's so many of them.
Among the first to come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramon, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many of them that I can talk all day about the bass players I love.
How did Pearl Jam succeed in keeping grunge relevant even though it’s no longer in vogue?
I think we all feel a certain detachment from the word grunge.
When I think of him, he reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone that came out at the same time, and if it’s important now, I think it’s wonderful because it’s music that’s worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are making music better now than ever.
At first, your music was darker, but now it has become more positive.
How would you explain this change?
That’s interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the album that might seem easier, but there are songs like The End or Just Breathe that are considered very dark, although they may sound a little positive.
Both of them, when Ed played them, I cried when I listened to them, these songs are very dark.
I think when you grow up and there’s been some trauma in your life and you’ve lost a family member or a friend, these events start to affect your creativity and your music, and these two songs, of course, reflect that for me.
So, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to create dark music.
