MSS Announces Obesity Gene Search Program
Social Protection Leads Study to Find Obesity Gene in Children and Young People; Supported by IPN Experts
The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect the obesity gene in children and young adults, which is called the protocol “Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence”, which will provide a count of signs associated with overweight.
In his statement, the head of the Department of Medical Research in Biochemistry of the Specialized Hospital of the National Medical Center of the XXI Century, Miguel Cruz Lopez, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was assembled.
This team is assisted by specialists and graduate students of the National Institute of Health of the Nation (NIPH) and the Center for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (prescribed or not) is invited to take part, going to the MSSI sports centers participating in the study, in the valley of Mexico City, where every Saturday, from 8:00 in the morning will be tested with the participation of children.
He stressed that the protocol began to be conducted at the sports center in Cuautemoca (in the west of the state of Mexico), and from October 8, the events are held at the sports center in Nezahualcoyotl (east of the state of Mexico).
Once the goal of attracting 500 to 600 children is achieved, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Center (south of Mexico City) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of Mexico City).
He explained that the purpose of this study is to understand the components and importance of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and to establish a risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, and the main goal is to collect three thousand children and adolescents aged 6 to 14 years with the permission of their parents and under their supervision to fill out individual nutritional questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturday, anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist circumference), measurements of blood pressure and glucose, fat, cholesterol and insulin levels, and genetic analysis (to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity) will be carried out.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez said the study reflects health care professionals’ concern about the alarming weight gain among children.
In medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006, it is said that in just 6 years there was an increase: in the case of boys 77 percent were obese, in the case of girls 47 percent; in the case of overweight, there was also a significant increase, "- said the specialist MSSI.
He said that the validity of the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that, on average, the Mexican is 65 percent descended from American Indians, 30 percent descended from Europeans and five percent descended from Africans, and this condition affected genes that are associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that the main consequence of obesity genetics is the body’s inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories), and it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the participants’ immediate benefit is a comprehensive assessment of the children, which can reveal whether they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck (acanthas) and forearms means the likelihood of metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
With information treated with complete confidentiality, doctors pass it on in writing to parents, to whom they explain all the measurements and lifestyle changes that must be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three main causes of overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of the TV and using transport over short distances instead of walking.
It also happens because of the high calorie intake, that is, the increase in the consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamaley, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetic predisposition analyzed in this program.
UNAM asphalt will be able to avoid cracks
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, has developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of the best quality, resistant to environmental and temperature influences.
If the signals sent by the road surface were given attention, it would be necessary to repair about 200,000 pits for each rainy season in the metropolitan area of the Valley of Mexico City, says Rafael Herrera Nahera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, and adds that if the process of building and maintaining the asphalted road surface is correct, then the number of pits can be reduced or even reduced.
In his lecture Technological Perspective on Pits, delivered as part of the International Year of Chemistry, it is reported that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture with characteristics close to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen can be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and therefore counteract the formation of pits.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some high molecular weight called asphaltenes, and others low molecular weight called maltenes, which together give the road surface its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscous behavior of bitumen lies in the fact that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it retains an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes brittle, he said.
This means that the resistance of street asphalt is not constant, but changes throughout the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, said a specialist in chemical engineering.
He noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexible coating that consists of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the uppermost layers is bitumen, composed of small stones lowered into the bitumen and then compressed.
Every stone that makes up this coating, he said, is submerged in bitumen.
When driving vehicles and exerting effort, it helps the forces to be very well distributed over the road surface.
If it were modified asphalt, they would be even better distributed, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt coating, he added, placed the last layer, which is called the wear layer, which is made of fine stone, in fact the sand is also submerged in asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will be in contact with the wheels of transport, it should have more resistance than asphalt coating and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute these forces, the wear layer also requires proper thickness, and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the state of asphalt.
When the earth is raw, water penetrates the coating and it is difficult to get out of it, this causes softening of all layers of the coating and, therefore, the formation of pits.
