Introduction of the “golden rule” of the budget into the Constitution
The leadership of the large coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to write the budget “golden rule” into the constitution to reduce the budget deficit and thus avoid a possible downgrade by rating agencies of the state credit rating of Austria (triple A).
Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann personally announced the decision at the end of a meeting of the Council of Ministers, despite the fact that the Austrian public debt is 74.6%, which is significantly higher than the upper threshold of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty, but below the public debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
If Austria’s solvency were to fall by just one point, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay interest on three thousand million euros more each year, argued Vice-Chancellor and Foreign Minister from Christian Democrats Michael Spindelegger.
Thus, Austria is meeting the demand of the Eurozone summit on October 26 in Brussels; heads of state and government demanded a reduction of budget deficits by the end of 2012 and a return to balanced public accounts through a constitution or equivalent law.
The decree adopted by the Austrian government resembles the “German model”, as Germany was the first European country to adopt this “rule”.
Until 2017, the structural deficit of the state budget should be reduced by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) every year, and from 2017 the structural deficit of the state budget of a federal state in any year should not exceed 0.35% of GDP, and the lands, like the communes, should represent balanced budgets.
The aim is to force public debt to fall below the 60% mark set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/2021.
