Energy policy:
The facts must prevail over the dogmas.
If there is a topic on which a decision cannot be made after a short discussion or under the influence of emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is a healthy trend that election meetings are becoming an occasion to reflect on the share and place occupied by nuclear energy.
The dispute will not bear fruit until all the economic, social and environmental implications of the options proposed have been explored.
France must base its opinion on objective facts and on rational data.
We are now 7,000 million people on the planet, demographic development will entail doubling the need for electricity by 2050, unless the vast majority of the world’s population is deprived of vital elements.
During the same period, it will become necessary to fill the growing shortage of fossil resources in order to continue producing electricity continuously, not forgetting the crucial need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate imbalances – a topic that has disappeared from environmental debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these factors.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
This is not the case in Belgium, which makes its decision dependent on the need to find a source that can replace nuclear energy, or Switzerland, which intends to build only the most modern reactors.
On the other hand, the UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil are just a few of those who are resolutely continuing their projects.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add one installation to its kit, resuming construction of the station, which was interrupted after the accident on Three Mile Island.
Although Germany’s renewable energy model is sometimes cited as an example, the reality contradicts this argument.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the cost of electricity, increased energy dependence, aggravated by the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, a jump in carbon dioxide emissions in connection with the construction of gas and coal plants.
After a few months, all these unpleasant effects will already be felt.
The example of Denmark should be considered.
The European champion in turbine construction, from which it receives 30% of its electricity, it is also the largest consumer of coal and gas due to intermittent wind; which makes carbon dioxide emissions and electricity prices respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbors pay 40% more for electricity than French households.
Since in a globalized economy the price of energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of maintenance of industrial equipment in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Consequently, any significant reduction in nuclear power will lead to a large increase in the cost of electricity, which will make illusory beautiful statements about the new industrialization of our country and the protection of purchasing power.
The price that most French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not object to this type of energy in principle.
It should be remembered that the country's energy policy made it possible to create an industry with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect ones.
Strongly export-oriented, it attracts a whole galaxy of specialized international trade small and medium-sized enterprises and creates many jobs that cannot be moved to another industry.
If France decided to give up nuclear energy, it would have to sacrifice a large number of these enterprises and lose 6 thousand million euros a year from French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What kind of electrical engineer would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years if its manufacturer were to be shut down?
To solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there are no divine or diabolical sources of energy production.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is undoubtedly a vital issue.
In France, we have a security body that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing energy centres such as Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is universally recognized, are full of the same obsession with security.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry had experienced three major incidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions, but without any human or environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, reactor design and unforgivable human error led to tragedy.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident occurred as a result of two natural disasters of unprecedented force that resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it learned from the previous two.
The fruit of this step and the cooperation between the security authorities, operators and French and German designers, EPR, represents a project to counter such phenomena.
As it is being considered by all energy professionals looking to build a reactor, stopping its construction in Flamanville will be a great gift to rivals Areva and EDF, clearing the way for them to gain leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best combination of energy sources for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and biased maneuvers to prevail in a dispute that is so important for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or a benefit to the economy?
The immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various sides – the overload of police, judicial and administrative services, subordinated to the policy of figures and the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France as a “human rights state”.
Then there was the administrative harassment of foreign students, which got into the news when the Minister of the Interior (Liberation, May 23) said that France “does not need foreign talents, masons and waiters.”
But it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The left and right seem to agree on a lot of things.
On the right was Jacques Chirac, who in 1976 declared that “900,000 unemployed will not be a problem in a country with 2 million foreign workers,” and on the left was Michel Rocard, who explained in 1990 that France “cannot accept the poor from all over the world.”
The only difference is the level of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the territory of the hordes of Polish plumber felt both left and right.
Both sides see immigration as a burden on the French economy and on French society.
The difference is only in the level of generosity they allow to be shown to immigrants.
In his program, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande limited himself to platitudes, saying that “working together will solve our immigration problem.”
This notion of immigration as a burden and a problem may give an electoral advantage, but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron remind us in a recent book summarizing recent data on immigration (Special People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Determined Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages, and employment in countries.
Limiting immigration weakens growth and reduces employment.
Fears of the impact of immigrants are based on the notion that they are able to replace local workers, especially low-skilled ones, provoking wage cuts.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants complement much more than they replace the local workforce by doing jobs for which there is a shortage of local labor.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract the local workforce, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training is not linked to job offers.
Positive Impact on Wages
Just as it would be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, the complementarity existing between local and immigrants leads to the fact that the arrival of immigrants positively affects the wages of local workers.
Giovanni Peri estimated that a 1% increase in migration leads to an increase of 0.6-0.9% in real long-term wages.
And this is without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of new ideas and economic growth (among the American Nobel Prize winners, a large proportion of naturalized immigrants, and Google, Intel, Paypal and Yahoo - all were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also bring net income to social security systems, giving an average of 1% of the total budgets of European countries.
According to the World Labor Organization, for example, in Germany, an immigrant, having arrived at the age of 30, will bring to the state budget for his life a net profit (income minus expenses) of an average of 150,000 euros.
Nicolas Sarkozy at the beginning of his mandate was going to "teeth" to cling to the missing points of growth.
These teeth, which were used to scare off immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it remains to comprehend European democracy
Democracy is a valuable acquisition, but at the same time it is fragile.
The European continent must remember that, having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, in the 20th century it survived the tragedies of World War I, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the Gulag, as well as Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and the colonels in Greece.
Some believed that for democracy to finally triumph over its enemies, it was enough to arrange a vote and make it as direct as possible.
Since the time of Napoleon "Little" it is known that this comes from the superficiality of thinking.
A universal vote, while a prerequisite for democracy, is not a sufficient condition for it and may even become an “instrument of repression,” as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vashro once said.
No, democracy requires much more - public space, public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of authorities, education, education, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The European crisis that we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but first and foremost it is a political crisis and a crisis of democracy.
In this respect, the palinody of the true-false Greek referendum will have a double expository effect, demonstrating both the need for a serious policy change and the unpleasant feeling of its impossibility and inconsistency.
This duality must be understood in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front line of the struggle for democracy has now shifted and, in the opinion of many, Republican soldiers are now aiming in the wrong direction.
We will gain nothing by demanding a series of national referendums, organised as necessary and in a chaotic manner.
"Carte blanche" for an absolute European monarch or a leap with legs tied into the abyss of nationalism - what a choice for a citizen!
No, we do not dream of a guillotine blade, but of a common, clear and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at the pan-European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal, and it is unknown how many more will have to be listed, because there is only one crisis - the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is completely subject to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffering from its weakness and lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is humiliated on the international stage.
Many are worried about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but the whole of Europe is gradually losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
It is urgent to return the management of the European project to popular sovereignty.
Because only by working together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of everyone’s debts, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing in them.
The way out of the crisis will require solutions at the pan-European level, and they cannot be adopted without full democratic legitimacy, without leading us to disaster.
After a long discussion of this proposal, the Socialists and Jacques Delors all now demand a European economic government.
Let's do it.
But to imagine it without stronger economic, political and democratic integration, which has come into force in the city, is another madness and a new dead end.
We need to start a new phase of European construction.
In order to establish a republic in France, it was necessary to “create” republicans.
A revolution of interests would not be enough.
This lesson remains in force.
We must build a Europe that is united on an economic level.
This can only be done by creating a more democratic Europe at the political level, a true people’s European sovereignty.
To create Europe, let us create Europeans.
