Terrorist Front Spreads from Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about the Islamic Maghreb’s ties to the Boko Haram sect.
Long-sought links between the al-Qaeda terrorist group in the Muslim Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian Boko Haram sect have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algeria’s deputy foreign minister, Abdelkader Messahel, even said Algerians were now confident.
“The way these two organizations operate and the intelligence reports show that they are actively cooperating,” he explained, without elaborating.
Paris seems to have come to similar conclusions.
An investigation into the abduction of two French men in Niger in January found two links.
Abducted in a restaurant in Niamey by people close to Aqmi, Antoine de Lecours and Vincent Deloris were apparently killed the next day along with several of the kidnappers during an operation conducted by French special forces.
Among the wreckage left after the operation, French and Nigerian investigators found several phone SIM cards belonging to terrorists.
The Axis of Terror
Analysis of the calls indicated several interlocutors in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), investigators are particularly interested in two numbers; one points to a Nigerian who has long lived in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a person allegedly close to Aqmi and to the sect.
“This is a step forward, but we certainly need to wait for more reliable evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
"It has been known for many years that the sect is receiving financial and ideological support from outside and that it is becoming more and more active," Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher, said in a statement.
In recent months, this support has become increasingly evident from Boko Haram’s actions and statements and its methods, which now include the use of suicide bombers and increasingly sophisticated explosive devices of the same type that Aqmi uses.
The international community, led by Washington, is now putting pressure on Abuja to pay attention to the problems that Boko Haram is creating.
The fact is that the Nigerian authorities have traditionally regarded this group as a community of enlightened people, of no interest.
Quick Success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri at a mosque, school and under the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram – which in Hausa means “Western education is a sin” – preaches the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the organization has achieved rapid success.
It is politicized and demands strict adherence to sharia, and its activists have launched a struggle against the wicked central government.
It is aimed mainly at churches, bars and authorities.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active in carrying out numerous attacks on police stations.
Abuja’s reaction, as usual, is uncompromising.
The army blockaded the city and left 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, taken alive, was killed in prison.
Now the sect will radicalize and go beyond its northern fiefdoms.
Last Christmas, she claimed responsibility for an action that killed 80 people in Jos, and then another in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram staged the first suicide attack on a fortified police headquarters in Abuja.
In August, the local representation of the United Nations will be their first international goal.
The establishment of a terrorist axis in Africa, which runs from Mauritania through Nigeria to Somalia, is now a concern for all security experts.
Today, with Aqmi entrenched in Mali and Niger and al-Shabaab Somalis operating in Kenya, Boko Haram poses a new threat to the continent.
Last week, during a conversation with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned of the dangers of Boko Haram and expressed his willingness to share all the information available.
The World as Seen by Republican Presidential Candidates
With regard to China, Iran and aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain and Rick Perry compete in simplification and incompetence.
Can a crisis-weakened America lead a complex world through simple, or rather simplistic, ideas?
If you listen to Republican presidential candidates, voters would believe it.
For several days now, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and others have been multiplying loud but undetailed statements on foreign policy, which have traditionally been a strength of the Republicans.
The slogans concerning China, Iran and aid to Israel are often mixed with each other.
Mitt Romney, who has the best chance of being nominated by the “Good Old Party,” threatened to file a complaint with the WTO against the Chinese and accuse them of “manipulating their currency is a sensitive topic for America, irritated by the migration of entire industries to Asia.
Even worse, if it leads to a trade war, he said.
John Huntsman, Obama’s former ambassador to China and the only candidate with a grasp of complex foreign policy, has been unable to overcome a position that indulges emotions.
He called for a firm but constructive dialogue with Beijing (Obama’s current position).
But Huntsman, who is held at the bottom of the ratings, remained unheard.
In the style of Reagan
Romney also promised military strikes on Iran if sanctions fail to stop its nuclear program.
“If I am elected, I will stop Iran,” he said.
“If Obama gets re-elected, they’ll have a bomb.”
He also pledged to step up military assistance to Israel, accusing Obama of failing to keep promises to that partner.
Entrepreneur Herman Kane, second in the ranking of candidates, demonstrated a discouraging ignorance of the cases.
He recently called for countering China’s military threat because Beijing is trying to achieve nuclear power – apparently without knowing that China has already possessed it since 1964!
Texas Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and is seeking military strikes on Iran, says he is ready to use the U.S. military in Mexico against drug cartels.
The use of torture on terrorism suspects, banned by Obama in 2009, is also recommended by Kane, Perry and candidate Michelle Bachman.
All this is very far from the 2008 Republican candidate John McCain, the heavyweight of foreign policy.
Opponents of the current president say that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he won the Cold War.
They recall that Obama himself was an amateur and that he had to tone down the fight against terror.
They rightly insist on the failure of his naive dialogue with Iran, the premature withdrawal of the “guys” from Iraq, his tricks in Libya, which have earned him a reputation as a weak politician.
But the offensive is not so simple.
The population considers the balance of national security under Obama, which eliminated Ben-Laden, to be positive.
After Iraq, it does not believe in military interventions that get bogged down in the sand.
And, arguing that America needs to be rebuilt economically to revive its leadership, Obama is right.
Nord Stream, a new gateway for Russian gas to enter Europe.
The Nord Stream gas pipeline connecting Western Europe and Russia directly along the bottom of the Baltic Sea has been launched.
It is designed to supply the equivalent of 30 million households with gas.
Gazprom, the Russian giant gas producer, wanted to celebrate this event with a pomp.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended last Tuesday on the Baltic coast, between the orchestra’s performance and exquisite snacks, at the opening of Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany underwater.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Francois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart, Mart Rutte, together turned the symbolic valve that controls the flow of Russian gas into the Western European network.
The new gas pipeline of 27.5 thousand million additional cubic meters of gas will be supplied to Western Europe every year through the first 1,224 km long pipeline connecting the Leningrad region with the land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline should be ready by the end of 2012, providing a total of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas equivalent to all of France’s consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met fierce resistance from Poland and the Baltic states.
Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose some of their power: they will find it more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
In the most intense moment of the debate, Warsaw did not stop at comparing the Nord Stream with the new “German-Soviet Pact”, hinting at an alliance between Hitler and Stalin with the aim of occupying Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is seeking greater security of its supplies.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to achieve its understanding of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries that consume large amounts of gas and whose own reserves are already at an end.
“This pipeline is part of the cooperation with Russia, it’s a new artery that organically connects us,” Francois Fillon argued, opening the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are important both politically and economically.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the heads of Gazprom, who were present in large numbers in Lyubmin, the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel enclosed in concrete to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It lies at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, it was necessary to bypass the minefields left over from the Second World War.
“One hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution,” Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller, a spokesman for Nord Stream, said.
It was also necessary to take many steps to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal snake weighing the weight of 242 Eiffel Towers, without ruptures along its entire length, without valves and without service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but the project managers abandoned it, because Sweden was not happy that the Russian state-owned company would settle on its shores forever.
“In the event of an accident, we will cut off the flow of gas in less than a minute,” says Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
So, in the event of a leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline will go into the air.
But this seems unlikely to designers who have designed seams designed to leak only once every 100,000 years.
Control of the gas pipeline will be carried out by an underwater robot that pulls the ship for external observation, as well as an apparatus circulating inside the gas pipeline.
The cigar-shaped apparatus is introduced into the pipeline with a diameter of 1 meter and pushed forward by a stream of gas.
Upon arrival after 3 full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second, it provides accurate information about any deformation of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without the need for the slightest repair.
Circulation of gas is carried out only due to its pressure.
It is 200 bar on departure and 100 bar on arrival.
Five companies joined forces to carry out the project.
The leader is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5 percent each), Dutch Gasunie and French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies set up a joint venture called Nord Stream, which was tasked with building and operating the pipeline.
Its headquarters are in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favorable.
Then Gazprom leased this company for twenty years with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
“Gazprom will pay for the full volume, regardless of how much gas will actually be transported,” says Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
Financing for the construction of the gas pipeline was provided by 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works will be 7.4 thousand euros for two pipelines.
GDF Suez’s investment will be around 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will pay back their costs, because Gazprom takes all the risks.
The gas pipeline leaves the Baltic Sea in Lyubmin to the sandy shore, planted with coniferous trees.
Valves 4.5 meters high form the gas outlet terminal.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before pumping it into German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has received one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour, and in 2012 it will be 6 million.
Brand Notebook Moleskine
Moleskine, created by an Italian company fifteen years ago, will return the taste to the letter.
It has the scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
Moleskine notebook is easy to recognize by a rectangular black cover, by a rubber band, by yellowish-white pages, as if yellowed with time.
However, the Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, located in Milan, decided to launch designer notebooks.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, took responsibility for launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique, moleskin - lacquered cotton fabric, used, for example, to cover benches.
It is claimed that this type of notebooks are highly valued by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine brought an old and forgotten thing into line with today’s taste that was iconic for avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” said Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand’s managing director at Modo Modo.
Success has come.
From 2006 to 2010, sales grew by 25% and reached 12.7 million units.
We are far from the production of the first years, when only 3000 notebooks were produced.
Moleskine has crossed the borders of Italy and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
Establishing the profile of a typical buyer is difficult, because the notebook equally attracts a businessman, a student and a person of a free profession.
Moleskine buyers are cosmopolitan, broad-minded and educated.
The small Italian company, which initially had only 12 employees, now has 100 and two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in Fnac bookstores, shops in the centers of small towns and was able to gain wide fame.
“We followed the spirit of the times and this new need for writing despite the advent of email,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This characteristic cultural trait accompanies the development of Moleskine; the brand recently organized an exhibition called “The Round Path”, where architects and artists showcased their own notebooks.
In August, he also launched covers with a leopard print on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its successes and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products, which now include handbags, pens, computer bags. The brand includes all kinds of support.
A success that gave rise to envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which has written a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate among disabled workers so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week of employment for disabled people begins today.
Despite the public charity policy launched in 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people is still twice as high as the average, namely 19% against 9% for the general population.
Disheartening?
“No,” said Eric Blanche, CEO of Adapt, an organization that organizes disability employment week.
“There has been a lot of progress in 15 years.”
“At that time, the share of the unemployed was not 2, but 3 times more.”
“But there is still a lot of work to be done.”
It must be said that for a disabled person there are still many obstacles to employment.
Among them, there are more elderly: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a rather low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor’s degree, and out of 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85% for people with disabilities, compared to 38% on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to return to work and that are at the heart of the problem,” according to Christian Grapen, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about a mentality that is changing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association on behalf of Cité found that the managers interviewed had a low level of knowledge about disability and "imagine solid people in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally disabled."
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the goal of having 6% disabled workers set in a law passed in 1987.
The last known figures relating to 2008 give a value of 2.6%.
“Today we are about 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting tax from companies that do not comply with the law.
Evidence: the number of “taxable” organizations, as well as the amounts paid, decreased in 2007-2011 from 59,000 to 46,000 organizations (and from <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>606 million to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>480 million).
“The 2005 law, which raised the tax, put a lot of pressure on companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects a rise in awareness, particularly in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of organizations with 20 to 49 employees have disabled workers against 82% of organizations with 100 to 199 employees.
